<HEADLINE>
TRUKU TRIBE LAUNCHES TRIBAL LANGUAGE DICTIONARY
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  April 11 (CNA) 04/11/07  18:54:04 (By Ruth Wang)
</P>
<P>
Hualien County's Hsioulin Township Office held a book launch for
an abridged dictionary and textbooks of Truku tribal language at
the Council of Indigenous Peoples (CIP) in Taipei City early
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
CIP Deputy Chairman Icyang Parod attended the book launch to
congratulate the Turuku tribe on its success in converting its
verbal language into written text.
</P>
<P>
Parod said that after Truku was officially recognized as a
Taiwanese aboriginal tribe in January 2004, Hsioulin Township
office invited tribal scholars and respected elders to edit this
dictionary. The completion of the dictionary is a monument to the
tribe, Parod added.
</P>
<P>
Hsioulin Township head Hsu Shu-yin said at the book launch that
the tribe took the initiative in editing its own dictionary and
textbooks. In addition to the book launch, Hsu said the township
will hold family tour activities on weekends from April 14-June
17 to promote tribal culture and industry.
</P>
<P>
Activities including an ecology tour, tribal music appreciation,
hunting, bamboo shoot picking, and a tribal antique exhibition,
will be held at the county's Pratan Tourist Center, Mukumugi
Visitor Center, and cultural parks, Hsu said.
</P>
